06634nam a22008055i 9780822393047DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223930477 a10.1515/97808223930472doi  a(DE-B1597)552424  a(OCoLC)709610574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a152.422204aThe Affect Theory Reader /ced. by Gregory J. Seigworth, Melissa Gregg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b1 photograph  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tAn Inventory of Shimmers -- tONE Impingements -- t1 Happy Objects -- t2 The Future Birth of the Affective Fact -- t3 Writing Shame -- tTWO Aesthetics and the Everyday -- t4 Cruel Optimism -- t5 Bitter after Taste -- t6 An Ethics of Everyday Infinities and Powers -- tTHREE Incorporeal/Inorganic -- t7 Modulating the Excess of Affect -- t8 After Affect -- t9 The Affective Turn -- tFOUR Managing Affects -- t10 Eff the Ineffable -- t11 On Friday Night Drinks -- t12 Desiring Recognition, Accumulating Affect -- tFIVE After Affect -- t13 Understanding the Material Practices of Glamour -- t14 Affect’s Future -- tAfterword: Worlding Refrains -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis field-defining collection consolidates and builds momentum in the burgeoning area of affect studies. The contributors include many of the central theorists of affect—those visceral forces beneath, alongside, or generally other than conscious knowing that can serve to drive us toward movement, thought, and ever-changing forms of relation. As Lauren Berlant explores “cruel optimism,” Brian Massumi theorizes the affective logic of public threat, and Elspeth Probyn examines shame, they, along with the other contributors, show how an awareness of affect is opening up exciting new insights in disciplines from anthropology, cultural studies, geography, and psychology to philosophy, queer studies, and sociology. In essays diverse in subject matter, style, and perspective, the contributors demonstrate how affect theory illuminates the intertwined realms of the aesthetic, the ethical, and the political as they play out across bodies (human and non-human) in both mundane and extraordinary ways. They reveal the broad theoretical possibilities opened by an awareness of affect as they reflect on topics including ethics, food, public morale, glamor, snark in the workplace, and mental health regimes. The Affect Theory Reader includes an interview with the cultural theorist Lawrence Grossberg and an afterword by the anthropologist Kathleen Stewart. In the introduction, the editors suggest ways of defining affect, trace the concept’s history, and highlight the role of affect theory in various areas of study.Contributors. Sara Ahmed, Ben Anderson, Lauren Berlant, Lone Bertelsen, Steven D. Brown, Patricia Ticineto Clough, Anna Gibbs,Melissa Gregg, Lawrence Grossberg, Ben Highmore, Brian Massumi, Andrew Murphie, Elspeth Probyn, Gregory J. Seigworth, Kathleen Stewart, Nigel Thrift, Ian Tucker, Megan Watkins  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAffect (Psychology). 0aCulture. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAhmed, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAhmed, Sara.1 aAnderson, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlant, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlant, Lauren.1 aBertelsen, Lone, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Steven D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo